<manpage>
    <sample url="sdk\operating_system\crt\libc\math\asin">asin</sample>
    <title> asin</title>
    <volume>C Run-Time Library Functions</volume>
    <routine_idx> math_idx.htm </routine_idx>

    <description>
        <para>The asin function compute the principal value of the arcsine of x. A domain error occurs for arguments not in the range [-1, +1].</para>
    </description>

    <syntax>
        <return_val>double</return_val>
        <func_name>asin</func_name>
        <parameters>
            <func_param>
                <param_type>double</param_type>
                <param_name>x</param_name>
                <param_note>
                    <para>Value whose arcsine is to be calculated.</para>
                </param_note>
            </func_param>
        </parameters>
    </syntax>

    <return>
        <para>The asin function returns the arcsine of x in the range еCдл/2 to дл/2 radians. If x is less than -1 or greater than 1, asin returns an indefinite (same as a quiet NAN).</para>
    </return>

    <requirements>
        <routine>
            <routine_name>asin</routine_name>
            <headerfile>math.h</headerfile>
            <compatibility>ANSI, Windows 2000, Elastos 2.0</compatibility>
        </routine>
    </requirements>

    <example>
<pre>
//==========================================================================
// Copyright (c) 2000-2004,  Elastos, Inc.  All Rights Reserved.
//==========================================================================

/* asin.cpp: This program uses asin to calculates the arcsine.
 */

#include &lt;math.h&gt;
#include &lt;stdio.h&gt;

int main()
{
    double x = 0.32696, y;

    y = asin(x);
    printf(&quot;Arcsine of %f = %f\n&quot;, x, y);

    return 0;
}
</pre>
    </example>
<result>
Arcsine of 0.326960 = 0.333085
</result>



